There is another possibility, which essentially uses another key as the
&quot;shift&quot; key.&nbsp; For
example, &quot;j&quot; combined with a following letter on a mapped keyboard to
shift to another letter.&nbsp; This works better than using the shift key
all the time because your right forefinger is over the &quot;j&quot; so it is
faster to hit it than to go to the shift key.&nbsp; It also makes more
sense to me than attempting to have a new keyboard manufactured.&nbsp; I
cannot believe that would cost effective for a very long time, i.e.
until we need a lot more keyboards than we would at present.&nbsp; The other
problem with that is that people aren&#39;t always at the same computer.&nbsp;
Since a newly&nbsp; designed keyboard would be a big change from the
standard we are used to, I wonder how that would affect touch typing
speed?&lt;br&gt;
